        "---\n",
        "## 8. Overview of Results\n",
        "\n",
        "### Overview\n",
        "Across six statistical tests, **priority level** emerged as the dominant predictor of dispatch\n",
        "response time, producing the only medium-sized effect in the analysis. All other significant\n",
        "predictors — incident category and time of day — showed small effects, while weekend status\n",
        "and local crime rate showed no meaningful relationship with response time.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Test 1 — Response Time by Priority *(Kruskal-Wallis, H=2911.36, p<0.001, ε²=0.104)*\n",
        "Priority level has a statistically significant and practically meaningful effect on response\n",
        "time. P0-Emergency calls received a median response of **4.6 minutes**, nearly three times\n",
        "faster than P4-Standard calls at **13.6 minutes**. Post-hoc testing confirmed that all\n",
        "priority pairs are significantly different from one another — with one notable exception:\n",
        "**P1-High and P2-Medium are statistically indistinguishable** (p=1.0), suggesting these two\n",
        "levels receive effectively equivalent dispatch urgency in practice.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Test 2 — Response Time by Incident Category *(Kruskal-Wallis, H=540.00, p<0.001, ε²=0.019)*\n",
        "Incident category has a statistically significant but small effect on response time. **Violent\n",
        "incidents received the fastest median response at 6.3 minutes**, followed by Trespassing (7.0\n",
        "min) and Domestic calls (7.6 min). **Parking incidents were the slowest at 14.1 minutes**.\n",
        "While these differences are operationally intuitive, the small effect size (ε²=0.019) indicates\n",
        "that incident category explains relatively little of the overall variation in response time\n",
        "beyond what is already captured by priority level.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Test 3 — Weekend vs. Weekday *(Mann-Whitney U, U=83,430,554, p<0.001, r=-0.053)*\n",
        "Although the test is statistically significant, the effect size is negligible (r=-0.053).\n",
        "Weekend response times were marginally faster than weekday (median 8.2 vs. 8.9 minutes, a\n",
        "difference of 0.67 minutes). This likely reflects lower call volume on weekends offsetting\n",
        "any reduction in staffing. **In practical terms, there is no meaningful weekend effect on\n",
        "response time.**\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Test 4 — Type Change and Incident Duration *(Mann-Whitney U)*\n",
        "The type-change analysis produced a split result. When an incident's type changed between\n",
        "initial dispatch and close, **response time was not significantly affected** (p=0.127,\n",
        "r=0.034) — which is expected, as the type change typically occurs on scene after arrival.\n",
        "However, **total incident duration was significantly longer** for type-changed incidents\n",
        "(median 51.2 vs. 38.8 minutes, a difference of 12.4 minutes; r=0.186, small effect). This\n",
        "suggests that incidents requiring reclassification are meaningfully more complex to resolve,\n",
        "even if they are reached at the same speed.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Test 5 — Local Crime Rate and Response Time *(Spearman, district-level: ρ=-0.086, p=0.872)*\n",
        "No significant relationship was found between district-level crime volume and median response\n",
        "time (p=0.872). With only six police districts, this test had very low statistical power and\n",
        "should be interpreted cautiously. The row-level correlation was statistically significant\n",
        "(ρ=-0.021, p=0.001) but negligibly small, indicating that crime density in a district does\n",
        "not meaningfully predict how quickly officers arrive at individual incidents.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Test 6 — Response Time by Time of Day *(Kruskal-Wallis, H=721.03, p<0.001, ε²=0.026)*\n",
        "Time of day has a statistically significant small effect on response time. **Late Night hours\n",
        "(midnight–5am) had the fastest median response at 6.5 minutes**, while Morning (9.8 min) and\n",
        "Afternoon (9.6 min) were the slowest — periods of peak call volume where resources are most\n",
        "stretched. Post-hoc testing found that Morning and Afternoon were not significantly different\n",
        "from each other (p=0.327), but all other time-of-day pairs were distinct.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Summary\n",
        "| Predictor | Effect Size | Practical Significance |\n",
        "|---|---|---|\n",
        "| Priority level | Medium (ε²=0.104) | Strong — 3× difference P0 vs. P4 |\n",
        "| Incident category | Small (ε²=0.019) | Modest — violent fastest, parking slowest |\n",
        "| Time of day | Small (ε²=0.026) | Modest — late night fastest, daytime slowest |\n",
        "| Weekend | Negligible (r=-0.053) | None — 0.67 min difference |\n",
        "| Type change → duration | Small (r=0.186) | Moderate — 12 min longer for complex incidents |\n",
        "| Type change → response | Negligible (r=0.034) | None |\n",
        "| Crime rate (district) | Negligible (ρ=-0.086) | None — insufficient geographic resolution |\n",
        "\n",
        "These findings inform the modeling phase: **priority, time of day, and incident category**\n",
        "are the strongest candidate predictors of response time, while weekend status and local crime\n",
        "density are unlikely to contribute meaningfully to a predictive model."
